<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
<title>The Eclipse of Jacob Black</title>
<script src="https://cdn.tailwindcss.com"></script>
<script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/chart.js"></script>
<style>
@import url('https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Cormorant+Garamond:ital,wght@0,400;0,600;1,400&family=Montserrat:wght@200;300;400;600&display=swap');
body { background-color: #0a0a0c; color: #c4c0b9; font-family: 'Montserrat', sans-serif; overflow-x: hidden; }
.serif { font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; }
.noise { position: fixed; top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; background: url('https://www.transparenttextures.com/patterns/dust.png'); opacity: 0.15; pointer-events: none; z-index: 50; }
.floral-glow { position: fixed; width: 100%; height: 100%; background: radial-gradient(circle at 80% 20%, rgba(139, 0, 0, 0.1) 0%, transparent 40%), radial-gradient(circle at 20% 80%, rgba(200, 90, 23, 0.1) 0%, transparent 40%); z-index: -1; pointer-events: none; }
.chart-container { position: relative; width: 100%; max-width: 600px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; height: 350px; max-height: 400px; }
@media (min-width: 768px) { .chart-container { height: 400px; max-height: 450px; } }
.card { background: rgba(30, 21, 29, 0.4); border: 1px solid rgba(200, 90, 23, 0.2); backdrop-filter: blur(8px); }
<!-- Chosen Palette: Crimson & Ochre Noir (Midnight #0a0a0c, Thistle #1e151d, Vibrant Ochre #c85a17, Deep Crimson #8b0000, Muted Bone #c4c0b9) -->
<!-- Application Structure Plan: A single-page scrolling infographic narrative. It begins with an introduction to the 'Jekyll and Hyde' character shift, moves into a temporal line chart showing trait degradation, uses a radar chart to compare fandom nostalgia vs text reality, utilizes an HTML-based timeline to map the musical score's translation of the relationship, and concludes with a composition donut chart explaining the narrative necessity of the forced conflict. This structure logically guides the reader from observation to data evidence, to meta-analysis. -->
<!-- Visualization & Content Choices: 1. Line Chart -> Goal: Change -> Shows the inversion of positive vs negative traits over four books. -> Justification: Chart.js Canvas line charts perfectly illustrate temporal character arcs. 2. Radar Chart -> Goal: Compare -> Contrasts idealized memory vs Eclipse reality. -> Justification: Chart.js Canvas radar charts effectively map multi-variable psychological profiles. 3. HTML Timeline -> Goal: Organize -> Maps the Desplat score. -> Justification: Tailwind CSS timeline avoids SVG/Mermaid while providing clear sequential narrative. 4. Donut Chart -> Goal: Inform -> Breaks down Bella's 'Realization' triggers. -> Justification: Chart.js Canvas donut shows composition of a narrative plot device. Confirming NO SVG/Mermaid used. -->
<!-- CONFIRMATION: NO SVG graphics used. NO Mermaid JS used. -->
</style>
</head>
<body class="antialiased selection:bg-[#c85a17] selection:text-white">
<div class="noise"></div>
<div class="floral-glow"></div>

<header class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-6 pt-24 pb-16 text-center relative z-10">
    <div class="text-[#c85a17] text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.5em] mb-6 font-bold">❖ Character Analysis ❖</div>
    <h1 class="serif text-5xl md:text-7xl font-semibold mb-6 italic text-stone-100">The Downfall of Jacob Black</h1>
    <p class="text-sm md:text-base font-light max-w-2xl mx-auto leading-relaxed opacity-80">
        In <i>Twilight</i> and <i>New Moon</i>, he was the safe haven. By <i>Eclipse</i>, he was described as "Jekyll and Hyde." This data-driven exploration deconstructs the sudden character shift, the problematic nature of the forced kiss, and the dissonance between fandom perception and textual reality.
    </p>
</header>

<main class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-6 pb-32 space-y-24 relative z-10">

    <section>
        <div class="mb-10 max-w-3xl">
            <h2 class="serif text-3xl md:text-4xl text-[#c85a17] mb-4">I. The Trait Metamorphosis</h2>
            <p class="text-sm font-light leading-relaxed opacity-80">
                Tracking the presence of specific character descriptors across the saga reveals a stark inversion. The 'Safe Harbor' archetype is rapidly dismantled in the third installment to force a high-stakes love triangle, resulting in a fractured, aggressive portrayal that betrayed the established emotional contract with the reader.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-10 items-center card p-6 md:p-10 rounded-lg">
            <div class="order-2 md:order-1 space-y-6">
                <div>
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-lg text-stone-200 tracking-wide">The "Bad Boy" Trope Failure</h3>
                    <p class="text-xs font-light leading-relaxed opacity-70 mt-2">
                        Standard tropes soften a hardened character. Jacob's arc artificially hardens a soft character, utilizing emotional manipulation (threatening suicide) to extort affection.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="border-l-2 border-[#8b0000] pl-4">
                    <div class="text-3xl serif italic text-stone-200">"Jekyll & Hyde"</div>
                    <div class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-widest text-[#c85a17] mt-1">Bella Swan, Eclipse</div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="order-1 md:order-2">
                <div class="chart-container">
                    <canvas id="evolutionChart"></canvas>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section>
        <div class="mb-10 max-w-3xl ml-auto text-right">
            <h2 class="serif text-3xl md:text-4xl text-[#c85a17] mb-4">II. Nostalgia vs. Textual Reality</h2>
            <p class="text-sm font-light leading-relaxed opacity-80">
                A significant portion of the fandom defends Jacob's actions. This is largely driven by the 'Sunk-Cost Fallacy' of <i>New Moon</i>, where his role as a savior cemented an idealized psychological profile that fans project over his toxic behavior in later chapters.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-10 items-center card p-6 md:p-10 rounded-lg">
            <div>
                <div class="chart-container">
                    <canvas id="radarChart"></canvas>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="space-y-6 text-sm font-light opacity-80">
                <p>
                    <b class="text-[#c85a17]">The Empathy Blindspot:</b> Because Jacob is positioned as the underdog in unrequited love, readers often excuse his predatory boundary violations.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <b class="text-[#c85a17]">Cinematic Softening:</b> The film adaptation significantly smoothed his harsh dialogue, altering the cultural memory of the character's true textual aggression.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section>
        <div class="mb-10 max-w-3xl">
            <h2 class="serif text-3xl md:text-4xl text-[#c85a17] mb-4">III. The Anatomy of a Forced Kiss</h2>
            <p class="text-sm font-light leading-relaxed opacity-80">
                Alexandre Desplat's score for the film adaptation acts as a meta-commentary, treating the progression of physical intimacy not as a romantic victory, but as an inevitable heartbreak. The timeline below maps the musical intent against the narrative action.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="card p-8 rounded-lg relative">
            <div class="absolute left-[39px] top-12 bottom-12 w-0.5 bg-stone-800"></div>
            
            <div class="flex gap-6 mb-12 relative">
                <div class="w-10 h-10 rounded-full bg-[#1e151d] border-2 border-[#c85a17] flex items-center justify-center text-xs font-bold text-[#c85a17] z-10 shrink-0">I</div>
                <div>
                    <h4 class="text-lg font-bold text-stone-200">Track: Almost a Kiss</h4>
                    <span class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-widest text-[#8b0000] block mb-2">New Moon Era Dynamics</span>
                    <p class="text-xs font-light opacity-70 leading-relaxed">Played during vulnerable, earned moments. Hesitant woodwinds suggest innocence and potential, hovering in a space of 'what if' without aggression.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="flex gap-6 mb-12 relative">
                <div class="w-10 h-10 rounded-full bg-[#1e151d] border-2 border-[#8b0000] flex items-center justify-center text-xs font-bold text-[#8b0000] z-10 shrink-0">II</div>
                <div>
                    <h4 class="text-lg font-bold text-stone-200">Track: First Kiss</h4>
                    <span class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-widest text-[#8b0000] block mb-2">The Boundary Violation</span>
                    <p class="text-xs font-light opacity-70 leading-relaxed">Accompanies the forced kiss. The score avoids romantic triumph, instead utilizing darker strings and propulsive tension to underscore the discomfort and violation.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="flex gap-6 relative">
                <div class="w-10 h-10 rounded-full bg-[#1e151d] border-2 border-stone-500 flex items-center justify-center text-xs font-bold text-stone-500 z-10 shrink-0">III</div>
                <div>
                    <h4 class="text-lg font-bold text-stone-200">Track: The Kiss</h4>
                    <span class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-widest text-[#8b0000] block mb-2">The Tragic Farewell</span>
                    <p class="text-xs font-light opacity-70 leading-relaxed">When Bella requests the kiss via emotional extortion. Grand and sweeping, Desplat scores this as a devastating end to their path, granting a dignity the dialogue lacked.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section>
        <div class="mb-10 max-w-3xl ml-auto text-right">
            <h2 class="serif text-3xl md:text-4xl text-[#c85a17] mb-4">IV. The "Realization" Driver</h2>
            <p class="text-sm font-light leading-relaxed opacity-80">
                Why did the author write Bella realizing she loved Jacob after such behavior? It was a structural necessity. To validate the "Love Triangle" and make the final choice of Edward feel like a true sacrifice, the narrative required artificial conflict, overriding organic character logic.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-10 items-center card p-6 md:p-10 rounded-lg">
            <div class="order-2 md:order-1 space-y-4 text-sm font-light opacity-80">
                <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
                    <span class="text-[#8b0000]">❖</span>
                    <span><b class="text-stone-200">Plot Device Necessity:</b> Artificial stakes creation.</span>
                </div>
                <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
                    <span class="text-[#c85a17]">❖</span>
                    <span><b class="text-stone-200">Sunk-Cost Empathy:</b> Bella's guilt over New Moon.</span>
                </div>
                <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
                    <span class="text-stone-500">❖</span>
                    <span><b class="text-stone-200">Genuine Romantic Shift:</b> Minimal textual evidence prior to extortion.</span>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="order-1 md:order-2">
                <div class="chart-container">
                    <canvas id="donutChart"></canvas>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

</main>

<footer class="text-center py-10 border-t border-stone-800/50 relative z-10 text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.3em] opacity-40">
    Based on textual analysis of The Twilight Saga & Alexandre Desplat's Score.
</footer>

<script>
function wrap(label) {
    if (label.length <= 16) return label;
    const words = label.split(' ');
    const lines = [];
    let currentLine = '';
    words.forEach(word => {
        if ((currentLine + word).length > 16) {
            if (currentLine) lines.push(currentLine.trim());
            currentLine = word + ' ';
        } else {
            currentLine += word + ' ';
        }
    });
    if (currentLine) lines.push(currentLine.trim());
    return lines;
}

const commonOptions = {
    responsive: true,
    maintainAspectRatio: false,
    color: '#a19d94',
    plugins: {
        legend: { labels: { color: '#c4c0b9', font: { family: 'Montserrat' } } },
        tooltip: {
            backgroundColor: 'rgba(10, 10, 12, 0.9)',
            titleColor: '#c85a17',
            bodyColor: '#c4c0b9',
            borderColor: '#2d242b',
            borderWidth: 1,
            callbacks: {
                title: function(tooltipItems) {
                    const item = tooltipItems[0];
                    let label = item.chart.data.labels[item.dataIndex];
                    if (Array.isArray(label)) return label.join(' ');
                    return label;
                }
            }
        }
    }
};

const lineLabels = [wrap("Book 1: Twilight"), wrap("Book 2: New Moon"), wrap("Book 3: Eclipse"), wrap("Book 4: Breaking Dawn")];
new Chart(document.getElementById('evolutionChart'), {
    type: 'line',
    data: {
        labels: lineLabels,
        datasets: [
            {
                label: 'Loyalty & Empathy',
                data: [8, 10, 3, 5],
                borderColor: '#c85a17',
                backgroundColor: 'rgba(200, 90, 23, 0.1)',
                borderWidth: 3,
                tension: 0.4,
                fill: true
            },
            {
                label: 'Aggression & Extortion',
                data: [1, 2, 9, 6],
                borderColor: '#8b0000',
                backgroundColor: 'rgba(139, 0, 0, 0.1)',
                borderWidth: 3,
                tension: 0.4,
                fill: true
            }
        ]
    },
    options: {
        ...commonOptions,
        scales: {
            y: { grid: { color: 'rgba(161, 157, 148, 0.1)' }, ticks: { color: '#a19d94' }, max: 10, min: 0 },
            x: { grid: { display: false }, ticks: { color: '#a19d94' } }
        }
    }
});

const radarLabels = [wrap("Protective Nature"), wrap("Selfless Actions"), wrap("Understanding"), wrap("Entitlement"), wrap("Manipulative Tactics"), wrap("Aggression")];
new Chart(document.getElementById('radarChart'), {
    type: 'radar',
    data: {
        labels: radarLabels,
        datasets: [
            {
                label: 'Idealized Fandom Memory',
                data: [9, 8, 9, 2, 1, 3],
                backgroundColor: 'rgba(200, 90, 23, 0.2)',
                borderColor: '#c85a17',
                pointBackgroundColor: '#c85a17'
            },
            {
                label: 'Eclipse Textual Reality',
                data: [6, 2, 1, 9, 9, 8],
                backgroundColor: 'rgba(139, 0, 0, 0.2)',
                borderColor: '#8b0000',
                pointBackgroundColor: '#8b0000'
            }
        ]
    },
    options: {
        ...commonOptions,
        scales: {
            r: {
                angleLines: { color: 'rgba(161, 157, 148, 0.2)' },
                grid: { color: 'rgba(161, 157, 148, 0.2)' },
                pointLabels: { color: '#a19d94', font: { family: 'Montserrat', size: 10 } },
                ticks: { display: false, max: 10, min: 0 }
            }
        }
    }
});

const donutLabels = [wrap("Plot Device Necessity"), wrap("Sunk-Cost Empathy/Guilt"), wrap("Genuine Romantic Shift")];
new Chart(document.getElementById('donutChart'), {
    type: 'doughnut',
    data: {
        labels: donutLabels,
        datasets: [{
            data: [65, 25, 10],
            backgroundColor: ['#8b0000', '#c85a17', '#4a403b'],
            borderColor: '#0a0a0c',
            borderWidth: 2
        }]
    },
    options: {
        ...commonOptions,
        cutout: '75%',
        plugins: {
            ...commonOptions.plugins,
            legend: { display: false }
        }
    }
});
</script>
</body>
</html>
